04529nam a2200661Ia 9780292745131DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20132002txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927451317 a10.7560/7914802doi  a(DE-B1597)587451  a(OCoLC)1286807501  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aGV1469.3b.M43 2002 7aNON0000002bisacsh04a794.8/097322104aThe Medium of the Video Game /ced. by Mark J. P. Wolf. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource (223 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- tI The Emergence of the Video Game -- t1 The Video Game as a Medium -- t2 Super Mario Nation -- tII Formal Aspects of the Video Game -- t3 Space in the Video Game -- t4 Time in the Video Game -- t5 Narrative in the Video Game -- t6 Genre and the Video Game -- tIII The Video Game in Society and Culture -- t7 Hot Circuits: Reflections on the 1989 Video Game Exhibition of the American Museum of the Moving Image -- t8 Play It Again, Pac-Man -- t9 Archetypes on Acid Video Games and Culture -- tAppendix: Resources for Video Game Research -- tIndex -- tAbout the Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver a mere three decades, the video game became the entertainment medium of choice for millions of people, who now spend more time in the interactive virtual world of games than they do in watching movies or even television. The release of new games or game-playing equipment, such as the PlayStation 2, generates great excitement and even buying frenzies. Yet, until now, this giant on the popular culture landscape has received little in-depth study or analysis. In this book, Mark J. P. Wolf and four other scholars conduct the first thorough investigation of the video game as an artistic medium. The book begins with an attempt to define what is meant by the term "video game" and the variety of modes of production within the medium. It moves on to a brief history of the video game, then applies the tools of film studies to look at the medium in terms of the formal aspects of space, time, narrative, and genre. The book also considers the video game as a cultural entity, object of museum curation, and repository of psychological archetypes. It closes with a list of video game research resources for further study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aVideo gameszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aVideo gameszUnited States. 7aNON-CLASSIFIABLE.2bisacsh1 aBaer, Ralph H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKent, Steven L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlovin, Rochelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTews, Rebecca R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolf, Mark J. P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolf, Mark J. P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311074534440uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/79148040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292745131423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292745131/original  a978-3-11-074534-4  University of Texas Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles